# Approach
1) Initialise the previous, start, middle, and end pointers with null.
2) Use Morris Traversal to perform an inorder traversal.
3) Keep the first and last numbers that are not in ascending sequence, and the middle element is the number next to the first.
4) Swap first and last if there is a second (final) descending element; otherwise, swap first and mid.



# Complexity
- Time complexity:
 $$O(n)$$

- Space complexity:
 $$O(1)$$

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    void recoverTree(TreeNode* root) {
        TreeNode* prev = NULL, *first = NULL, *mid = NULL, *last = NULL;
        TreeNode* cur = root;
        while(cur){
            if(!cur -> left){
                if(prev and cur -> val < prev -> val){
                    if(!first){
                        first = prev;
                        mid = cur;
                    }
                    else last = cur;
                }
                prev = cur;
                cur = cur -> right;
            }
            else{
                TreeNode* temp = cur -> left;
                while(temp -> right and temp -> right != cur) temp = temp -> right;
                if(!temp -> right){
                    temp -> right = cur;
                    cur = cur -> left;
                }
                else{
                    temp -> right = NULL;
                    if(prev and cur -> val < prev -> val){
                        if(!first){
                            first = prev;
                            mid = cur;
                        }
                        else last = cur;
                    }
                    prev = cur;
                    cur = cur -> right;
                }
            }
        }
        if(first and last) swap(first -> val, last -> val);
        else if(first and mid) swap(first -> val, mid -> val);
    }
};
```

