solutions.content:
The question asks us to swap two values in a BST to make it valid.
##### But how do we know which elements are to be swapped?
As we know the inorder traversal of a BST is in ascending order. We need to swap the first greatest element with the last smallest element.
For eg. If we have our inorder traversal as: 5 2 3 4 1, we need to swap 5 and 1 such that 5 > 2 (first greatest element) and 4 > 1 (last smallest element)

A very straight-forward approach will be storing the inorder traversal of the invalid BST provided to us in a List and then checking which elements are to be swapped.

### Approach: 

```
    public void recoverTree(TreeNode root) {
        List<Integer> list = new ArrayList<>();
        getInorderList(root, list);

        int i = 1;
        Integer first = null, second = null; 

        // Getting the first largest element and last smallest element
        while (i < list.size()) {
            if (first == null && list.get(i - 1) > list.get(i))
                first = list.get(i - 1);
            if (first != null && list.get(i - 1) > list.get(i))
                second = list.get(i);

            i++;
        }

        swapValues(root, first, second);
    }

    public void getInorderList(TreeNode root, List<Integer> list) {
        if (root == null)
            return;

        getInorderList(root.left, list);
        list.add(root.val);
        getInorderList(root.right, list);
    }

    // Swapping the values of the two nodes in BST
    public void swapValues(TreeNode root, Integer num1, Integer num2) {
        if (root == null)
            return;

        if (root.val == num1) 
            root.val = num2;
        else if (root.val == num2)
            root.val = num1;

        swapValues(root.left, num1, num2);
        swapValues(root.right, num1, num2);
    }
```

This approach is time consuming and it uses extra O(n) space, to further optimize it, we can directly keep track of first and second nodes to be swapped while inorder traversing.

### Optimized Approach:

```
    // First and second nodes's values are to be swapped
    // Prev is used to compare current node to previous node
    TreeNode first = null;
    TreeNode second = null;
    TreeNode prev = new TreeNode(Integer.MIN_VALUE);

    public void recoverTree(TreeNode root) {
		inorder(root);

        // Swapping the values
        int temp = first.val;
        first.val = second.val;
        second.val = temp;
    }

    public void inorder(TreeNode root) {
        if (root == null)
            return;

        inorder(root.left);

        // If first isn't assigned we will make first equals to the greater value (prev)
        // If first is assigned we keep updating second to the smaller value (root)
        if (first == null && prev.val > root.val)
            first = prev;
        if (first != null && prev.val > root.val)
            second = root;

        prev = root;

        inorder(root.right);
    }
```

