solutions.content:
the key to solve this problem is : The **inorder traversal** of a BST produces a sorted array

1.  a simple method is to store inorder traversal of the input tree in an auxiliary array. Sort the auxiliary       array. Finally, insert the auxiliary array elements back to the BST, keeping the structure of the BST         same. The time complexity of this method is O(nLogn) and the auxiliary space needed is O(n).w can     also make here some optimization by using insertion sort(for minimum complexity).

2.  We can solve this in O(n) time and with a single traversal of the given BST. Since inorder traversal        of BST is always a sorted array, the problem can be reduced to a problem where two elements of a      sorted array are swapped. 

     Example : For example, Nodes 2 and 3 are swapped in [1,2,3]. 
                      The inorder traversal of the given tree is [3,2,1] 
	If we observe carefully, during inorder traversal, we find node 2 is smaller than the previous visited      node 3. Here save the context of node 3 (previous node). Again, we find that node 1 is smaller      than the previous node 2. This time, we save the context of node 1 (the current node ). Finally, swap the two node’s values.

	Example, Nodes 2 and 3 are swapped in [1,2,3,4]. 
  The inorder traversal of the given tree is [1,3,2,4]
  unlike previous example ,here only one point exists where a node value is smaller than the previous    node value.

    so, here we can note that when two elements of a sorted array are swapped. 
   There are two cases that we need to handle:
   Firts : The swapped nodes are not adjacent in the inorder traversal of the BST. 
   Second :  The swapped nodes are adjacent in the inorder traversal of BST.

    we can handle two cases by using FirstNode , SecondNode , PreviousNode For every node (except     the leftmost node of the tree), keep track of its previous node in prev. The current node being processed is stored in the curr.
If during the traversal, we find a node that violates the BST order  previousNode->val > CurrentNode->val .we store PreviousNode into fFirst and CurrentNode into Second.
During further traversal, if we find another node that violates the BST criteria , previousNode->val > CurrentNode->val. but since, the First node had been already assigned a value. so we assign the current node(which violates BST criteria) to Second.
After execution of inorder traversal. swap the data of First and Second nodes and The tree gets fixed.


```
    void RecoverBinarySearchTree(TreeNode* CurrentNode ,TreeNode* &PreviousNode ,TreeNode* &First, TreeNode* &Second) {
        if(CurrentNode == NULL) return;
        RecoverBinarySearchTree(CurrentNode->left,PreviousNode,First,Second);
        if(PreviousNode != NULL && PreviousNode->val > CurrentNode->val) {
            if(First == NULL){
                First = PreviousNode;
                Second = CurrentNode;
            }else Second = CurrentNode;
        }
        PreviousNode = CurrentNode;
        RecoverBinarySearchTree(CurrentNode->right,PreviousNode,First,Second);
    }

    void recoverTree(TreeNode* root) {
        TreeNode* First = NULL; TreeNode* Second = NULL; TreeNode* PreviousNode = NULL;
        RecoverBinarySearchTree(root,PreviousNode,First,Second);
        int temp = First->val;
        First->val = Second->val;
        Second->val = temp;
    }
```
