solutions.content:
Submitting a solution that passes all test cases of this problem is simple. However, there are two points of this problem setting that really do NOT make sense. Neither does the official solution article take them into account:
1. According to the official solution article and all test cases used in this problem, we know that it's assumed that there are no duplicate values in a tree, which is however never stated in the problem description.
In general, the definition of BST includes "equal" situation, namely: the value in each node is **greater than or equal to** (less than or equal to) any values stored in its left (right) subtree. So a BST does not necessarily have unique value for each node. 
So the question would be be: "how to handle duplicate cases?" which is raised already by many other guys in the Discussion part (see: https://leetcode.com/problems/recover-binary-search-tree/discuss/32673/Does-the-BST-in-this-problem-include-duplicate-nodes, https://leetcode.com/problems/recover-binary-search-tree/discuss/32656/How-to-handle-the-case-when-there-are-duplicate-values-in-the-BST, and [etc](https://leetcode.com/problems/recover-binary-search-tree/discuss?currentPage=1&orderBy=most_relevant&query=duplicate).)

2. It is assumed in this problem that it is the **values**(i.e., key of the node) of two nodes that got swapped. In a more reasonable setting, the two **TreeNodes** are swapped other than the mere values. (For example, in real application, a tree node might carry some satellite data.) In such scenarios,  we want a solution that swap nodes instead of just their (key) values.

**To address the above concerns:**


This is a more general solution that is able to handle duplicate values (only 1 pass)
```
# This solution uses stack. You can also do the similar thing with recursion or Morris traversal
# This solution is able to deal with duplicate values; therefore it's a more general solution
# (we assume the two swapped nodes don't have the same value.)
# Time complexity: O(N)
# Space complexity: O(H) where H is the height of the tree. In the worst case it can deteriorate to O(N)
class Solution:
    def recoverTree(self, root: TreeNode):
        """
        :rtype: void Do not return anything, modify root in-place instead.
        """
        stack = []
        x = y = pred = None

        while stack or root:
            while root:
                stack.append(root)
                root = root.left
            root = stack.pop()

            ### this is what we do to each traversed node ###
            if pred:
                if x is None:
                    if root.val < pred.val:
                        x = pred 
                        y = root
                else:
                    if root.val <= y.val:
                        y = root
                    if root.val > x.val:
                        break
            if pred is None or root.val != pred.val:
                pred = root
            ### this is what we do to each traversed node ###

            root = root.right
        x.val, y.val = y.val, x.val
```


If you also want to consider swapping nodes instead of values, here is what you need:
```
# This solution:
#    1. is able to deal with duplicate values
#    2. swaps nodes instead of values
# (we assume the two swapped nodes don't have the same value.)
# Time complexity: O(N)
# Space complexity: O(H) where H is the height of the tree. In the worst case it can deteriorate to O(N)
class Solution:
    def recoverTree(self, root: TreeNode):
        """
        :rtype: void Do not return anything, modify root in-place instead.
        """
        stack = []
        x = y = pred = None
        parent = None
        while stack or root:
            while root:
                stack.append((root, parent))
                root, parent = root.left, root
            root, parent = stack.pop()

            ### this is what we do to each traversed node ###
            if pred:
                if x is None:
                    if root.val < pred.val:
                        x, x_parent = pred, pred_parent
                        y, y_parent = root, parent
                else:
                    if root.val <= y.val:
                        y, y_parent = root, parent
                    if root.val > x.val:
                        break
            if pred is None or root.val != pred.val:
                pred, pred_parent = root, parent
            ### this is what we do to each traversed node ###

            root, parent = root.right, root
        swap_nodes(x, y, x_parent, y_parent)

def swap_nodes(x: TreeNode, y: TreeNode, x_parent: TreeNode, y_parent: TreeNode):
    if x_parent is y:
        if y_parent:
            if y_parent.left is y:
                y_parent.left = x
            else:
                y_parent.right = x
        if y.left is x:
            x.left, x.right, y.left, y.right = y, y.right, x.left, x.right
        else:
            x.left, x.right, y.left, y.right = y.left, y, x.left, x.right

    elif y_parent is x:
        if x_parent:
            if x_parent.left is x:
                x_parent.left = y
            else:
                x_parent.right = y
        if x.left is y:
            x.left, x.right, y.left, y.right = y.left, y.right, x, x.right
        else:
            x.left, x.right, y.left, y.right = y.left, y.right, x.left, x

    else:    
        x.left, x.right, y.left, y.right = y.left, y.right, x.left, x.right
        if x_parent:
            if x_parent.left is x:
                x_parent.left = y
            else:
                x_parent.right = y
        if y_parent:
            if y_parent.left is y:
                y_parent.left = x
            else:
                y_parent.right = x
```


Finally, I provide an optimal solution which has the asymtotically best time & space complexity (O(n) time and O(1) space) and also takes into account the aforementioned two points, using Morris traversal.

```
# Morris traversal
# This solution:
#    1. is able to deal with duplicate values
#    2. swaps nodes instead of values
# (we assume the two swapped nodes don't have the same value.)
# Time complexity: O(N)
# Space complexity: O(1)
class Solution:
    def recoverTree(self, root):
        """
        :type root: TreeNode
        :rtype: void Do not return anything, modify root in-place instead.
        """
        x = y = predecessor = pred = None

        node = root
        while node:
            if not node.left: 

                ### this is what we do to each traversed node ###
                if pred:
                    if x is None:
                        if node.val < pred.val:
                            x = pred 
                            y = node
                    else:
                        if node.val <= y.val:
                            y = node
                if pred is None or node.val != pred.val:
                    pred = node
                ### this is what we do to each traversed node ###

                node = node.right            
            else:
                predecessor = node.left
                while predecessor.right and predecessor.right is not node:
                    predecessor = predecessor.right

                if not predecessor.right:
                    predecessor.right = node
                    node = node.left
                else:
                    predecessor.right = None 

                    ### this is what we do to each traversed node ###
                    if pred:
                        if x is None:
                            if node.val < pred.val:
                                x = pred 
                                y = node
                        else:
                            if node.val <= y.val:
                                y = node
                    if pred is None or node.val != pred.val:
                        pred = node
                    ### this is what we do to each traversed node ###

                    node = node.right 

        x_parent, y_parent = self.morris_preorder(root, x, y)
        swap_nodes(x, y, x_parent, y_parent)

    def morris_preorder(self, root, x, y):
        '''
        This is used to find the parents of x, y in linear time and constant space
        '''
        node, parent = root, None
        while node:
            if not node.left: 

                ### check if we meet the parent ###
                if node is x:
                    x_parent = parent
                elif node is y:
                    y_parent = parent
                ### check if we meet the parent ###

                node, parent = node.right, node            
            else:
                predecessor = node.left
                while predecessor.right and predecessor.right is not node:
                    predecessor = predecessor.right

                if not predecessor.right:

                    ### check if we meet the parent ###
                    if node is x:
                        x_parent = parent
                    elif node is y:
                        y_parent = parent
                    ### check if we meet the parent ###

                    predecessor.right = node
                    node, parent = node.left, node
                else:
                    predecessor.right = None                     
                    node, parent = node.right, node

        return x_parent, y_parent
```
Note that if your implementation swaps nodes instead of values, then the code won't pass the test cases of this problem, since in some cases it swaps the root node and the LeetCode testing code of this problem won't change the pointer to the original root to the new root so that you eventually end up with a subtree instead of the original entire tree.

