Do inorder traversal. Find the node whose previous value and current node is not in order. (prevElement > currElement)
Keep track of first node and last node encountered like this and swap them.
**Explanation:** 
1.The inorder traversal of BST should always give us ascending order but not when nodes are swapped.
2.Now if we know the point where the order is violated, we can find the nodes which violate it and then swap them.
```
class Solution {
TreeNode preNode = null;
TreeNode firstNode =null, secondNode =null;

public void recoverTree(TreeNode root) {
    inorderTraversal(root);
    int temp = firstNode.val;
    firstNode.val = secondNode.val;
    secondNode.val = temp;
}
public void inorderTraversal(TreeNode curr) {
    if(curr == null)
        return;
    inorderTraversal(curr.left);
    //Do the work
    if(preNode != null) {
        if(preNode.val > curr.val) {
            if(firstNode == null) {
                firstNode = preNode;
            }
            secondNode = curr;
        }
    }
    preNode = curr;
    inorderTraversal(curr.right);
}
}
