solutions.content:
So, pretty straightfoward solution, if you ask me: BFS is the way to go and while I see it doable also with a DFS approach (either storing a lot more data in or building a painfully tricky backtrack system), I will once again fully and passionately embrace the [KISS approach](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/KISS_principle) on this one.

We start creating an empty vector `res`; if the tree is empty itself (ie: `!root`, then we just return it).

If not, we know we have at least one layer to grind through our BFS routine: we can initialise a queue container `layer` to store all the nodes at each level as we go and we pre-populate it with `root`.

A few more support variable might be worth initialisation here and we are going to dive into our breadth first search until `layer` has at least one surviving element.

Unlike other similar problems, here we can start directly from the end result - we push the rightmost value of each `layer` into `res`. And then we move on to populate `layer` for the next iteration, extracting each single note and checking if it has any `left` or `right` children to pass down.

Once there are no more nodess to be scanned, we are finally done and we can return `res`.

The code:

```cpp
class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> rightSideView(TreeNode* root) {
        vector<int> res;
        // exiting with an empty tree
        if (!root) return res;
        // some useful variable initialisation
        queue<TreeNode*> layer;
        layer.push(root);
        int len;
        TreeNode *currNode;
        // BFS loop
        while (layer.size()) {
            // first of all, let's update res
            res.push_back(layer.back()->val);
            // then let's prepare layer for the next run
            len = layer.size();
            while (len--) {
                currNode = layer.front();
                layer.pop();
                if (currNode->left) layer.push(currNode->left);
                if (currNode->right) layer.push(currNode->right);
            }
        }
        return res;
    }
};
```

Can we do better? Probably, since queues are hardly the top performing solution you might get for this kind of problem.

And going with a DFS is still cool, nevertheless.

To solve this problem, we then refactored and created `res` at class level and then called the helper function `dfs` to populate it.

This function is taking 2 parameters, `root` (our starting node) and `layer` (defaulted to `0`).

At each call, we will:
* just `return` is `root` is `NULL`;
* store the value of the current node:
	* replacing the current value of `res[layer]` when there was already one (`res.size() > layer`), since we proceed with a preorder, so we know that the last element is always the rightmost);
	* add it to `res` otherwise;
* recursively call it `dfs` on the `left` and `right` branches.

Once done, we can just return `res`.

The code:

```cpp
class Solution {
public:
    // support variable
    vector<int> res;
    void dfs(TreeNode *root, int layer = 0) {
        // edge case: no node
        if (!root) return;
        // updating the node on that layer if existing
        if (res.size() > layer) res[layer] = root->val;
        // adding it to res if there was no previous element
        else res.push_back(root->val);
        // recursive calls
        dfs(root->left, ++layer);
        dfs(root->right, layer);
    }
    vector<int> rightSideView(TreeNode* root) {
        dfs(root);
        return res;
    }
};
```

